{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"66fba1b6-af77-47d6-a558-326efe2a7d4e","content":"Use **dotnet-trace** — it's lightweight, doesn't need Visual Studio, and works great for .NET 8.\n\n### Quick steps\n\n```powershell\n# Install (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds is usually enough)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope** (https://speedscope.app).\n\n### Tips\n- **Don't restart the service first** — capture while CPU is hot.\n- If you can't install global tools, use `--tool-path C:\\tools` instead.\n- For deeper OS-level analysis (kernel + managed), use **PerfView** directly — it captures ETW events and gives flame graphs, but has a steeper learning curve.\n- Convert to speedscope format for easy sharing: `dotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope`","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"58bcb891-fc1a-4467-8314-3ecf15aa9eb5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":312},"id":"aa47a8dc-6333-4be5-a6e7-e7f348f25c85","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:46:48.186Z","parentId":"9414b850-fc81-4f6c-a276-1fe4bc760c70"}
